"""ML/AI deep dive — transformer details, training tricks, evaluation, modern architectures."""
LESSONS=[
    ('What is the difference between encoder, decoder, and encoder-decoder transformers?','Encoder-only (BERT): bidirectional attention, good for understanding/classification. Decoder-only (GPT, Llama, Claude): causal (left-to-right) attention, good for generation. Encoder-decoder (T5, BART): encoder processes input, decoder generates output attending to it. Modern: most LLMs are decoder-only with massive scale; encoder-decoder for translation/summarization tasks.'),
    ('What is multi-head attention?','Split Q, K, V into H heads (each smaller). Run attention in parallel per head. Concatenate + project. Lets the model attend to different relationship types simultaneously — some heads track syntax, others semantics. Typically 8-128 heads in modern models. Cost: same FLOPs as one big head; benefit: richer representations.'),
    ('What is positional encoding?','Tokens have no inherent order in attention — positional encoding tells the model where each token is in the sequence. Original: sinusoidal. Modern: RoPE (rotary position embeddings, used in LLaMA + most new LLMs), ALiBi (linear bias), learned positional embeddings. Critical for: extending context length, generalizing to longer sequences.'),
    ('What is RoPE?','Rotary Position Embeddings. Encode positions by rotating query + key vectors by angles proportional to position. Has nice property: relative positions encoded in attention scores naturally. Used in: LLaMA, Mistral, most modern LLMs. Variants (NTK-aware, YaRN) extend context length beyond training.'),
    ('What is KV cache in LLM inference?','During generation, you process one token at a time. Re-computing attention K + V for previous tokens is wasteful. Cache them. Memory cost: O(layers * heads * seq_len * head_dim). For long contexts → huge memory. Modern optimizations: paged attention (vLLM), multi-query attention (MQA), grouped-query attention (GQA) reduce KV cache size dramatically.'),
    ('What is MQA vs GQA vs MHA?','Multi-Head Attention (MHA): N query heads, N key/value heads. Standard. Multi-Query (MQA): N query heads, 1 shared K/V — small quality loss, big memory + speed win. Grouped-Query (GQA): N query, G groups of K/V. Middle ground. Modern models (LLaMA 2+, Mistral): GQA standard.'),
    ('What is RLHF?','Reinforcement Learning from Human Feedback. Pipeline: (1) collect human preference data (which of two model outputs is better?). (2) train reward model to predict preferences. (3) fine-tune LLM via RL (PPO) to maximize reward. Used to align base models with human preferences (helpfulness, harmlessness). Alternatives: DPO (direct preference optimization, no separate reward model).'),
    ('What is DPO?','Direct Preference Optimization. Alternative to RLHF that skips the reward model + RL. Directly optimizes language model to prefer chosen responses over rejected ones using a contrastive loss. Simpler + more stable than PPO-based RLHF. Adopted by many modern open models (Llama 3, etc.).'),
    ('What is constitutional AI?','Anthropic\'s training technique. Model uses self-critique + revision based on a "constitution" of principles. Generates initial response, critiques per constitution rules, revises. Then trains on the revisions. Reduces need for human preference labels. Foundation of Claude\'s alignment.'),
    ('What is in-context learning?','LLMs can adapt behavior from examples in the prompt WITHOUT updating weights. Few-shot: 3-5 examples → model pattern-matches. Mechanism not fully understood — appears to invoke transient task-specific computation. Cost: long prompts (more tokens, more $). Benefit: no fine-tuning needed for many tasks.'),
    ('What is a context length and how do you extend it?','Max tokens model can handle in one forward pass. Trained context limits practical use. Extensions: (1) positional embedding tricks (RoPE NTK scaling, YaRN) — extend beyond training. (2) attention modifications (sliding window, ring attention, Mamba SSM). (3) retrieval-augmented generation — fetch relevant chunks instead of stuffing all. Long-context evals matter (needle-in-haystack tests).'),
    ('What is quantization in LLMs?','Reduce precision of weights from fp16/bf16 to int8 / int4 / smaller. Cuts memory by 2x / 4x / more. Inference faster too (lower bandwidth). Trade-off: small quality loss (usually negligible at int8, more noticeable at int4). Methods: GPTQ, AWQ, bitsandbytes nf4. Lets you run 70B models on consumer GPUs.'),
    ('What is LoRA?','Low-Rank Adaptation. Freeze pretrained model; train small low-rank matrices added to each weight matrix. <1% of full fine-tuning cost in params + memory. Many task-specific LoRAs can be swapped at runtime. Foundation of personalization in image models (Stable Diffusion) + cheap LLM fine-tuning. Use HF peft library.'),
    ('What is QLoRA?','LoRA + 4-bit quantized base model. Lets you fine-tune 65B+ models on a single consumer GPU. Quality matches LoRA on full-precision base. Standard technique for fine-tuning at home / on a budget.'),
    ('What is flash attention?','Memory-efficient + faster attention implementation. Computes attention in tiles that fit in SRAM (close to compute), avoiding repeatedly reading/writing the attention matrix (O(N²) memory normally). FA2/FA3 successive improvements. Standard in modern training stacks (PyTorch, JAX) — 2-4x speedup with no quality change.'),
    ('What is the difference between MLP and attention in transformers?','Attention: mixes tokens — each output token is a combination of all input tokens, weighted by similarity. MLP (feedforward block after attention): per-token transformation, doesn\'t mix tokens. Together: attention provides "what to look at," MLP provides "how to compute on it." Roughly equal parameters.'),
    ('What is mixture of experts (MoE)?','Multiple "expert" feedforward networks; router decides which experts handle each token (typically top-2 of ~8-64). Effective: same compute per token but much larger model capacity. Used in: Mixtral, GPT-4, DeepSeek. Trade-offs: memory holds all experts; load balancing important.'),
    ('What is the difference between SFT and pretraining?','Pretraining: next-token prediction on huge unlabeled text. Creates a "base" model. SFT (supervised fine-tuning): on (instruction, response) pairs, teach the model to follow instructions. Cheap relative to pretraining. RLHF/DPO further align. Modern chat models = pretrain → SFT → preference tuning.'),
    ('What is hallucination in LLMs?','Model generates confident-sounding but false statement. Caused by: pattern completion from training data may not match facts, model doesn\'t know what it doesn\'t know, missing grounding. Mitigations: RAG (provide sources), prompt for uncertainty ("if you don\'t know, say so"), fine-tune for honesty, post-hoc fact-check.'),
    ('What is chain-of-thought?','LLM technique: ask model to "think step by step" before answering. Improves accuracy on math, logic, multi-step problems. Modern reasoning-tuned models (o1, Claude with thinking) do this internally + automatically. For other models: prompt explicitly. Trade-off: more tokens (slower, more cost).'),
    ('What is the difference between greedy, beam, and sampling decoding?','Greedy: always pick highest-prob token. Deterministic, often repetitive. Beam search: track top-K partial sequences, expand each. Better for fixed-output tasks (translation). Sampling (temperature, top-p): pick from probability distribution, more diverse + creative. Most chat uses temperature ~0.7 + top-p ~0.9.'),
    ('What is speculative decoding?','Use a small "draft" model to predict the next N tokens; big model verifies in one forward pass. Accept matching prefix. Speedup if draft model is correct often (~2-4x). Modern inference engines (vLLM, TensorRT-LLM) implement.'),
    ('What is the difference between BLEU and ROUGE for evaluation?','Both compare generated text to references. BLEU: precision-oriented (how much of generation appears in reference). Used for translation. ROUGE: recall-oriented (how much of reference appears in generation). Used for summarization. Both have known limitations — don\'t capture semantic equivalence. Modern: also use LLM-as-judge, embedding similarity.'),
    ('What is perplexity?','Exp(average negative log-likelihood per token). Lower is better. Measures how "surprised" model is by text. Foundation eval for language models. Lower perplexity != better at tasks (subtle relationship). Use for: model comparison on same dataset; diagnosing degradation during training.'),
    ('What is BERT vs GPT in usage?','BERT: encoder-only, bidirectional attention. Best for: understanding (classification, NER, sentiment, embeddings). GPT-family: decoder-only, causal attention. Best for: generation, chat, code completion. Modern: same family of LLMs (Claude, GPT-4) do both via instruction tuning.'),
    ('What is an embedding model?','Neural network that maps text/image/etc to dense vector representations. Trained so semantically similar inputs are close in vector space. Examples: sentence-transformers (open), OpenAI text-embedding-3, Cohere embed, BGE, nomic-embed. Use for: semantic search, RAG, clustering, dedup.'),
    ('What is the difference between sentence-transformers and OpenAI embeddings?','sentence-transformers: open source, run locally, free, smaller models (~80MB-1GB), specific task tuning available. OpenAI embeddings: API-based, pay per token, larger model better quality on many tasks. Choose by: cost, latency, privacy needs. Modern open models (BGE, nomic) close the quality gap.'),
    ('What is the difference between embedding and tokenization?','Tokenization: split text into discrete units (tokens) — int IDs. Embedding: map each token (or whole sequence) to a continuous vector. Tokenization happens first; embeddings are computed by the model from token IDs. "Word embeddings" historically (Word2Vec) — now mostly contextual embeddings from transformers.'),
]
